voice_to_text: I said I want something big I want something that says I'm here Beyonce hi my name is Judy I'm a lactation consultant and let me tell you why it is actually so normal for your areolas to get darker and larger during pregnancy so it's likely due to all the hormone changes that you're going through and your body actually has an increase in melanin which causes your areolas to get darker and possibly other areas of your body and your skin could get darker as well some scientists also believe that darker and larger areolas can actually help your baby find and locate where to latch onto especially since their vision isn't fully developed yet at birth your areolas may return to its original size and color although the timing of when that will happen will vary could be anywhere from a few weeks to a few months postpartum and for some individuals it might just stay that way but isn't the human body such a crazy and beautiful thing

voice_to_text: absolute fact pirates are actually a lot more orderly and meticulous when attacking a ship than we might think hello everyone my name is Doctor Rebecca Simon and I'm historian of the golden age of piracy and give Pat a follow his videos are brilliant and this one is just top tier he's comparing and contrasting how pirates are depicted in films versus real life in terms of how they attack a ship in films pirates are often like our our matey kill kill kill but in real life it was actually pretty orderly you wanted to get in and out as fast as you can because pirates wanted to survive they didn't want any members of their crew to get killed so what they would often do would be using some sort of scare tactics such as Samuel Bellamy who he and his crew would charge naked on the ships or Blackbeard putting fuses in his beard but the reality is they pirates wanted to talk to the other captain they wanted to look at the manifest they wanted to look at the logs they wanted to see what goods they had so that way they could take what they needed to replenish their own ship and also sell you can read more about these pirate tactics in my book Pirates Code Laws and Life Aboard Ship

voice_to_text: hi I'm an academic of the Japanese language and culture and I can explain but before I explain I want to bring attention to posts which are supposed to be funny and instead create a sense of um kind of hopelessness in students because how am I going to remember all of this ah it makes no sense it makes sense it makes a lot of sense if you understand that the Japanese language like every other language we have available on earth today is the product of multiple millennia or at the very least multiple well no actually research about the Japanese language tends to date back to about the 6th century so it is a millennia and a half because we don't really know what exactly it sounded like before the 6th century for the fact that it didn't have a writing system so everything about it was reported by um people from countries who were visiting what eventually became Japan so giving you that context right what you need to understand is that Japanese kanji did not just magically happen one day when Japan adopted kanji they went through a sequence of steps to do so and that sequence of steps which as first was just shoe hoarding forcefully the Japanese pronunciation onto the kanji and then slowly adjusting it so that you have some characters which hold semantic meaning and some characters which hold phonetic meaning that means some characters were used for their meaning as a word and some characters were used specifically only for the sound and the mixture of that plus the development of the language in the people over the next centuries eventually LED to what we now modernly call Japanese so why is it sweet touchy and itchy nichy because they come from different points in time ichinichi is a newer word if I'm not mistaken so itachi is an older word how do we know that well because before Japan used the western calendar or whatever I forget which calendar it is that we all use now it use the lunar calendar and under the lunar calendar the first day of the month is the first day after the new moon when you start seeing the moon again which makes sense right and that used to be called Tsuki tachi as in Tsuki月 moon  tachi 立ちgoing up so the day of the month where you first saw the moon was the first day of the month over time of course people simplified that that pronunciation so they kept the kanji of day one but 月き　立ち was difficult to say so they smoothed it into ついたち and that's because just like in English taking out a back consonant makes it easier for you to say two words together right it's it's a little bit like how they also changed 書きても or 書きてto become 書いて notice how not having a "k" in the middle of a word makes it smoothe?  that's it I want people to understand that behind every linguistic choice that a language seems to have made it is not the language who made that choice it is the people and people across languages and cultures have a very predictable behavioural pattern and that is we want to say the most with the least effort cause we lazy and that is why spoken English and written English have to be taught separately even to native speakers nothing against the op because I see this format a lot and it's supposed to be entertaining and I get it however as somebody who really struggled before YouTube and everything to understand the Japanese language because teachers just kept saying oh it doesn't make sense it just it is what it is I want people to know that it isn't irrational just oh it is what it is it is a very logical and easily understandable shift but you need to have the context and when we teach languages again this is not criticism of the person when people teach languages in my experience what they tend to do is they teach the modern language with no context and like anything taken out of context things don't make sense so the reason why Japanese lettering, Chinese characters, have so many readings is because they didn't just happen overnight into what we now have as modern Japanese they had a 1400-year at least process of getting adapted and adopted into the Japanese language as it was at the time and so even if you look between the 7th century and the 9th century you can already see some pretty huge shifts in pronunciation and that is important because these pronunciation differences then got codified in kanji which then got codified in katakana and hiragana and then you have people some 12 centuries later who come from foreign countries who know nothing about this language and nothing about the people and just phonetically imitate what is happening now luckily for the Japanese they met people from a phonetic language background first because if they'd met English it would be even harder to understand what Japanese has been doing all these years since English is not a phonetic language everything makes sense if you have context and that reason being that  what humans make is based in the same principles and those principles cross language and culture barriers because they are human all languages come from humans that means the reasoning behind those languages is going to have common points and so that means that just because you think something doesn't make sense and is hilarious it is fine for it to be hilarious  and not make sense to you but what you have to understand is  you are not the keeper of all human wisdom so just because it doesn't make sense to you doesn't mean it doesn't make sense I hope this helps

voice_to_text: So I was addicted to nasal spray for many, many years, and I haven't used it ever since. I stopped. I hate to tell you guys this, but I relapsed on nasal spray this weekend. I was at Coachella in the desert, and the desert sand was in my nose, and I was so congested. And it's like, nasal spray is one of those things. I'm like, oh, I know I can fix this. Like, nasal spray would fix this. And I hate a stuffy nose. And so I just. I got it and it worked, and it was amazing, and I was like, ah! And I felt so much better. But now I used it, so I used it for three days in a row, which is exactly what you're not supposed to do. Like, so I can't use it another day. If you. If you hit that four day Mark, like, you are gonna start to get addicted to it. So let's break this down for a second. Not all needle sprays are created equally. There are nasal saline sprays, which just wash out your nasal passages. There are nasal antihistamine sprays, which can be used as needed. And it's similar to oral antihistamines, is just in a nasal formulation. There are nasal steroids sprays that could be used consistently for long periods of time without any issue. But there are nasal decongestant sprays. So things like Afrin that can be addictive and should not be used for More than a week, so three days, you should be fine. However, any longer than a week, you can develop something called rhinitis Medica Mentosa. So, basically, nasal decongestant sprays are so good at calming down the swollen blood vessels in your nasal passages that when you stop using it, they swell right back up again. The good news is, there are treatments available for you to get off of being on these nasal sprays, and so it's important to check with your doctor. We can get you off of those in

voice_to_text: uh first and foremost public service announcement don't get a dog like uh I think this is genuinely quite an important thing to consider if you're thinking of getting a dog are you happy to still walk your dog a couple of times a day even if it's raining all day everyday like it has been for weeks? actually it's quite interesting to think about why do we actually have pets in the first place? it seems like it has a really obvious answer to that question actually a a pet is a huge investment of your own resources uh of time and effort and money uh and anyone interested in this this book is well worth reading it's excellent it's called The Animals Among Us uh and it's by John Bradshaw who is an anthrozoologist  so he studies the relationship between humans and animals undoubtedly there were a huge benefits of having a pet in your life  you know of the companionship and the joy that they bring you and an unconditional love probably sums it up um but there's also yeah there are some positive effects on your mental health how your dog does force you to get out and exercise uh obviously there are service dogs assistance dogs that help people in a very direct way I think it's interesting that in the last 10 years pet ownership has been increasing alongside life possibly becoming more complicated and busy for a lot of people uh and I think this book sort of one of the um main reasons it suggest we have pets is that we are evolutionarily pre programmed to want to be around animals and with people increasingly living in cities and being more detached from nature having a pet in your life sort of fulfills the instinct to be around animals so it's really interesting um why do you have a pet it’s an interesting question

if your resume is getting auto rejected it means you're not getting past the ATS scanners and AI not true the ATS does not scan your CV the ATS does not determine whether you are suitable for the role or not based purely on your CV if you do get auto rejected that's because you have answered questions as part of their application form which is then determined whether you get rejected or pass through to a recruiter to review your CV so for example if one of the requirements for the role is that you need a full driving license if you answer the question that says do you have a full driving license and you say no then you will get auto rejected the ATS does not reject you based on your CV alone and normally the people that are telling you that ATS is will auto reject your CV usually the people are trying to sell you at ATS friendly CVS CV template CV writing services or access to platforms that will score your CV the ATS does not auto reject your CV there is no such thing if you do need help with your CV check out the link in my bio there's a completely free CV template that lots of people have downloaded and have told me is helping them get job interviews and if you want some actual real job search advice and not nonsense hit the follow button cheers
